replyContent:
1) Make sure you have location service enabled (required)
2) Make sure the app is allowed to run in background. Exclude it from any battery optimazation (third party tools as well as system integrated optimatations)
3) Don't add more than one WiFis to the preferred list - the app won't switch between those
Also see integrated help!

Only works with location services on. I try to only turn on location services temporarily as it uses up power. Looks like with this app it has to remain on to scan for Wi-Fi signals
replyContent: Yes, that's the Google policy since Android 6. Without location service WiFi scans are not possible. But when you set the location service to power save mode (no GPS required), it will hardly consume any battery power.

content: I've tried a number of these kind of apps, some with high ratings. However a lot of them don't specify the new connection and hope the OS is clever enough to connect to the correct access point if you disconnect and reconnect. Android 7.2 doesn't, it reconnects to the one it last connected to. This is in my opinion is essential in environments with multiple access points and solves that problem completely, 5 stars guys and thank you !.

Works well once the settings have been tweaked to suit your own Wi-Fi environment. I have a couple of Powerline network adapters in my house and there's a bit of overlap in coverage, so I had to reduce the strength differential to 10% to force it to switch to the nearest access point, but I'd fine tuned tuned the settings, it's brilliant. I was even able to increase the scanning frequency to every 15 seconds (while the screen is on) without  noticeably increasing battery usage.
